  "prompt": "I have an aversion to shaking hands with strangers. How can I avoid this and not be rude?",
  "response": "It's perfectly understandable to feel uncomfortable with shaking hands, and there are polite ways to navigate this situation without coming across as rude. Here are some suggestions:\n\n1. **Use a Different Greeting**: Offer a friendly wave, nod, or smile instead of extending your hand. This can signal openness without the need for physical contact.\n\n2. **Be Honest**: If the situation allows, you can explain that you prefer to avoid handshakes for personal reasons. Most people will understand and appreciate your honesty.\n\n3. **Adapt Your Greeting**: You can use phrases like \"I'm not a big handshaker\" or \"I prefer to keep my distance, but it\u2019s great to meet you!\" This makes your preference clear without sounding accusatory.\n\n4. **Offer an Alternative**: If appropriate, suggest a fist bump or an elbow bump as a more casual alternative to a handshake.\n\n5. **Practice Timing**: If you anticipate meeting someone new, think about how to introduce your greeting style early in the conversation. This sets the tone for the interaction.\n\n6. **Focus on Body Language**: Use positive body language and eye contact to convey warmth and friendliness, which can create a welcoming atmosphere even without physical contact.\n\n7. **Be Prepared**: Sometimes people may extend their hand automatically. In such cases, a gentle step back or a quick verbal cue can help redirect the interaction.\n\nBy applying these strategies, you can navigate social situations comfortably while maintaining a respectful demeanor.",
